1 Introduction to Shrinkage Estimat

Load the libraries

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

Data from the classic Efron/Morris paper on Shrinkage Estimators Data Analysis Using Stein’s Estimator and its Generalizations http://www.stat.cmu.edu/~acthomas/724/Efron-Morris.pdf

Baseball players go up to hit (an “At Bat”): sometimes they succeed, sometimes they fail. The proportion of successes is called the “batting average”. It is a estimate of the player’s “true” probability of success

The goal here is to predict the true probability of success from a limited sample (N=50). The “true” average is not known, but is assumed to be pretty much equal the player’s batting average at the end of the season (N=500 or so).

The original data set from the paper. Eighteen players, each with exactly 90 at bats. Players include Roberto Clemente, Frank Robinson, Frank Howard, Ron Santo, Bert Campaneris, and Thurman Munson

The values MLE are the current batting averages (proportions of success) after N=50 at bats (trials). From a strict frequentist perspective, the MLE is the “best” estimate of a player’s true probability of success.

Another strategy is to assume all the players are identical and we are just seeing random variation amoung the success rates. Hence, the best estimate for each player is just the pooled proportion of sucess.

Stein-James says the best individual estimator for each player is a compromise between these to estimators.

Get to work The number at bats (common to all).

AB0 <- 90

The key quantities. * M is Total number of observations. In this case, 18 * pbar=pooled average * sigma0 =estimated variance of of the pbar. * perr=estimated standard error (or so)

M <- nrow(bb.df)
(pbar <- with(bb.df,mean(MLE)))
## [1] 0.2536111
(sigma0 <- pbar*(1-pbar)/AB0)
## [1] 0.00210325
(perr <- with(bb.df,sum( (MLE-pbar)^2)))
## [1] 0.04796828
sigma0/perr
## [1] 0.04384669

The key quantity the shrinkage factor

(shrinkJS <- 1-(M-3)*sigma0/perr)
## [1] 0.3422997
bb.df <- bb.df%>%
    mutate(JS = pbar+shrinkJS*(MLE-pbar))
bb.df

A picture of the shrinkage

ggplot(bb.df) +
    geom_segment(aes(x=MLE,xend=JS,y=0,yend=1))+
    geom_segment(aes(x=TRUTH,xend=JS,y=2,yend=1))+
    geom_point(aes(x=MLE,y=0),color="red")+
    geom_point(aes(x=TRUTH,y=2),color="brown") +
    geom_point(aes(x=JS,y=1),color="blue")  +
    scale_y_continuous(limits=c(-0.5,2.5))+
    ggtitle("MLE (Red), JS (Blue), TRUTH (Brown)")

Loss functions: Pooled, MLE, and JS

lossPOOL <- with(bb.df,sum( (TRUTH-pbar)^2))
lossMLE <- with(bb.df,sum( (TRUTH-MLE)^2))
lossJS <- with(bb.df,sum( (TRUTH-JS)^2))
c(lossPOOL,lossMLE,lossJS)
## [1] 0.02661050 0.04251200 0.02125445

Filter on these

absUpdate.df <- bbUpdate.df%>%
    filter(event %in%abEvents)

Only consider batters with a reasonable number of ABs

batterTots.df <- absUpdate.df%>%
    group_by(batterID)%>%
    summarize(AB=n())%>%
    filter(AB>375)

Get the player IDs and take a random sample for our experiment

playerIDs <- with(batterTots.df,unique(batterID))
playerIDs <- sample(playerIDs,40,rep=F)

filter on these players and only keep relevent variables

absUpdate.df2 <- absUpdate.df%>%
    filter(batterID %in% playerIDs)%>%
    arrange(batterID,gid,inning)%>%
    select(batterID,event)%>%
    group_by(batterID)

Now grab all the hits and create a hit indicator Then create a running total of abs, hits and average

hit.ids <- which(events %in% c("Single","Double","Triple","Home Run"))
(hitEvents <- droplevels(events[hit.ids]))
## [1] Double   Home Run Single   Triple  
## Levels: Double Home Run Single Triple
absUpdate.df2 <- absUpdate.df2%>%
    mutate(HIT=event %in% hitEvents)%>%
    mutate(abNum=row_number(),
           hitNum=cumsum(HIT),
           aveCurr=hitNum/abNum)

absLast.df <- absUpdate.df2%>%
    group_by(batterID)%>%

Rename

names(absLast.df)[2:4] <- c("aveFinal","abFinal","hitFinal")

bbUpdate.df <- absAB0.df%>%

Compute these values for the James-Stein Estimator

(M <- nrow(bbUpdate.df))
## [1] 40
(pbar <- with(bbUpdate.df,mean(MLE)))
## [1] 0.2716667
(perr <- with(bbUpdate.df,sum( (MLE-pbar)^2)))
## [1] 0.1029506
(sigma0 <- pbar*(1-pbar)/AB0)
## [1] 0.002198488
(K <- (M-3)*sigma0/perr)
## [1] 0.7901268
(shrinkJS <- 1-K)
## [1] 0.2098732

The JS estimator of the TRUE average

bbUpdate.df <- bbUpdate.df%>%
    mutate(JS = pbar+shrinkJS*(MLE-pbar))
